The Challenges We Address

Solving compliance challenges head-on.

  • Data Quality and Accuracy 

    Inconsistent or inaccurate data across watchlists, customer records, and transactions undermines screening effectiveness and increases false positives/negatives. 

  • Scalability for High Data Volumes 

    Handling growing data volumes and processing them in real-time requires scalable infrastructure, particularly for transaction screening.

  • Timely Updates and Regulatory Alignment 

    Keeping systems updated with frequent regulatory changes (e.g., sanctions lists) while minimising latency is complex and resource-intensive.

  • False Positives and Negatives

    High false positive rates in screening systems lead to resource drains, while false negatives expose institutions to significant regulatory risks. 

  • Integration Across Systems

    Consolidating data from multiple sources (e.g., internal, third-party, and regulatory lists) into a unified framework is labour-intensive and prone to fragmentation.

  • Resource and Expertise Constraints

    Specialised skills in compliance, data science, and AI/ML are in short supply, impacting the ability to tune and optimise solutions effectively.  

  • Transparency and Audibility 

    Ensuring clear data lineage, audit trails, and explainability in decision-making is critical, especially with AI/ML-driven systems.

  • Privacy and Security

    Balancing data privacy with regulatory requirements for sensitive customer and transaction data remains a key concern.

  • Workflow and Tool Fragmentation

    Fragmented workflows and disparate tools across departments hinder compliance teams’ efficiency and increase operational risks.

  • Adapting to Rapid Industry Growth

    Adapting to evolving compliance needs while ensuring seamless integration with existing systems demands flexible, future-ready solutions.
